This paper discusses a decentralized protocol for achieving Byzantine fault tolerance, which is a topic commonly studied in distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper specifically focuses on safety, liveness, and execution consistency violations in the protocol, which are important aspects of security and cryptography (cs.CR). The scenarios presented in the paper involve replicas and clients communicating with each other, which is a common theme in distributed systems (cs.DS). The paper also discusses owner changes, which is a topic related to network infrastructure (cs.NI). Finally, the paper discusses a TLA+ specification used to model check the protocol, which is a formal methods technique commonly used in systems and control theory (cs.SY).
